snippet.textDisplay:
First, am I the only person who recalls that a pope some time ago, within living memory, reduced David, of Wales, George, of England, and Patrick, of Ireland, in rank to just being regular people. Second, cheese was never used in either the traditional Shepherd`s Pie or a Cottage Pie but if so it becomes a Cumberland Pie, which few have heard of or tasted. Cumberland Pie is much older than either of the other two and is traceable to Medieval times. Beer/stout or Madiera were never included in the recipe.

Third, look around the internet and cookbooks and see how many people, chef or home cooks "aka wannabe chefs" have put up recipes for Shepherd's Pie, Cottage Pie, or the travesty of Shepherd's Pie made in the USA which is, in reality, Cottage Pie. Also, look around for beef pie, in all of its imagined varieties and see how many purport to be the "original" version but are only variations of the original. The same goes for other British comfort foods such as Fish and Chips. Amazingly enough many are from people living in the USA and have never even visited our shores.

'nuf sed. plamuk aka travellingchef.

snippet.textDisplay: Shepherds pie is like a Bolognese sauce, you got your basics, but really it's a stew wish mash on it, the idea is to use left overs or whatever you like. I make a hen pie which is the same deal but chicken thighs in a white sauce, you could go white wine or cheesy and bang in some tarragon but again it's whatever you have. As long as it sticks to your ribs it's all good.
